 {"id":"franken_networkx-modzero","title":"REVIEW: [LOW] modularity on zero-edge graph returned 0.0 instead of raising ZeroDivisionError","description":"nx.community.modularity(G, partition) raises ZeroDivisionError on a graph with zero edges (the 2m divisor is 0). fnx's Rust path returned 0.0 silently. User code doing 'try: modularity(G, part) except ZeroDivisionError: skip' would see the fnx 0.0 and treat an undefined measurement as an actual value. Added the zero-edge guard in fnx's Python wrapper before delegating to Rust.","status":"closed","priority":4,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-24T10:42:30.000000000Z","created_by":"cc-networkx","updated_at":"2026-04-24T10:42:30.000000000Z","closed_at":"2026-04-24T10:42:30.000000000Z","close_reason":"Added zero-edge ZeroDivisionError before delegating to _raw_modularity","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"franken_networkx-preftree","title":"REVIEW: [MEDIUM] prefix_tree missing NIL terminal node + extra label attribute","description":"nx.prefix_tree adds a synthetic NIL terminal node at integer -1 with source='NIL' (present even for empty input). Every path ends with an edge from its last non-root node to NIL so path-reconstruction code can distinguish 'path ends here' from 'intermediate prefix'. fnx omitted the NIL entirely AND added a bogus 'label' attribute to non-root nodes that upstream does not have. User code doing 'for leaf in tree.predecessors(-1): ...' found no terminals and silently produced empty results. Fixed prefix_tree to emit the NIL terminal and to drop the 'label' attribute. dag_to_branching (which calls prefix_tree and strips the synthetic root) now also strips the NIL so its returned branching still matches nx exactly.","status":"closed","priority":3,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-24T10:49:35.000000000Z","created_by":"cc-networkx","updated_at":"2026-04-24T10:49:35.000000000Z","closed_at":"2026-04-24T10:49:35.000000000Z","close_reason":"Added NIL terminal + dropped bogus label attribute; dag_to_branching strips both","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"franken_networkx-grattrident","title":"REVIEW: [LOW] G.graph = {...} did not preserve dict identity","description":"The _GraphAttrsDescriptor __set__ stored the new dict directly instead of mutating the existing one. Test test_graph_attr_assignment_preserves_identity already encoded the expected in-place contract (before = G.graph; G.graph = {...}; assert before is G.graph) — matching nx's semantics where external references to G.graph continue to see updated contents after assignment. Fixed __set__ to clear-then-update when both sides are dict.","status":"closed","priority":4,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-24T10:49:35.000000000Z","created_by":"cc-networkx","updated_at":"2026-04-24T10:49:35.000000000Z","closed_at":"2026-04-24T10:49:35.000000000Z","close_reason":"__set__ now does in-place clear-then-update preserving dict identity","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
+{"id":"franken_networkx-mincutsig","title":"REVIEW: [LOW] minimum_cut / minimum_cut_value / minimum_node_cut parameter-name divergence","description":"fnx.minimum_cut and fnx.minimum_cut_value used 'G, source, sink' as param names; nx uses '_s, _t' (with underscore prefix). Kwarg-style 'nx.minimum_cut(g, _s=s, _t=t)' worked on nx but TypeError on fnx. fnx.minimum_node_cut used lowercase 'g' as first param; nx uses 'G'. Fixed both by renaming params to match nx exactly.","status":"closed","priority":4,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-24T11:02:03.000000000Z","created_by":"cc-networkx","updated_at":"2026-04-24T11:02:03.000000000Z","closed_at":"2026-04-24T11:02:03.000000000Z","close_reason":"Renamed params to match nx: _s, _t on minimum_cut*; G on minimum_node_cut","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
+{"id":"franken_networkx-kcompalgo","title":"REVIEW: [HIGH] k_components completely broken on non-trivial graphs","description":"fnx.k_components(G) implemented a naive filter: 'components whose global node_connectivity >= k'. That is not what nx.k_components computes. On karate_club_graph (node_connectivity=1 due to articulation points), fnx returned {1: [all 34 nodes]} while nx correctly returned {1: ..., 2: ..., 3: ..., 4: ...} via the Moody-White recursive algorithm on (k-1)-connected substructures. Compounded by the subgraph view passing: 'G.subgraph(comp)' returned a filtered view that the Rust node_connectivity rejected with TypeError on non-karate calls. Fixed by delegating to nx for correctness; also added flow_func kwarg parity. Native port deserves its own session.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-24T11:02:03.000000000Z","created_by":"cc-networkx","updated_at":"2026-04-24T11:02:03.000000000Z","closed_at":"2026-04-24T11:02:03.000000000Z","close_reason":"Delegated to nx for correct Moody-White algorithm","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
+{"id":"franken_networkx-kcompflow","title":"REVIEW: [LOW] k_components / edge_disjoint_paths / node_disjoint_paths missing parity kwargs","description":"k_components missing 'flow_func'; edge_disjoint_paths and node_disjoint_paths missing 'auxiliary' and 'residual'. Added at public surface for drop-in kwarg parity.","status":"closed","priority":4,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-24T11:02:03.000000000Z","created_by":"cc-networkx","updated_at":"2026-04-24T11:02:03.000000000Z","closed_at":"2026-04-24T11:02:03.000000000Z","close_reason":"Added missing parity kwargs","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
+{"id":"franken_networkx-ghtree","title":"REVIEW: [MEDIUM] gomory_hu_tree stringified nodes + dropped cut-value weight attrs","description":"The Rust fast-path _fnx.gomory_hu_tree_rust returned a tree whose node identifiers were stringified ('0','1' instead of int 0,1) and whose edges lacked the cut-value 'weight' attribute that nx's tree carries. Drop-in callers that read 'tree.edges[u,v][\"weight\"]' got KeyError; pattern-matching on node type broke. Delegated the whole function to nx for correctness.","status":"closed","priority":3,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-24T11:02:03.000000000Z","created_by":"cc-networkx","updated_at":"2026-04-24T11:02:03.000000000Z","closed_at":"2026-04-24T11:02:03.000000000Z","close_reason":"Delegated to nx for correct node types and weight attrs","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
+{"id":"franken_networkx-swmsg","title":"REVIEW: [LOW] stoer_wagner error messages didn't match nx's 3 distinct wordings","description":"nx raises 3 different messages: 'graph has less than two nodes.', 'graph is not connected.', and (implicitly) the compute path when valid. fnx raised one generic 'stoer_wagner requires a connected graph with >= 2 nodes' for all preconditions. Pre-validated in the Python wrapper so regex pytest.raises(..., match='graph has less than two nodes') against upstream keeps working.","status":"closed","priority":4,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-24T11:02:03.000000000Z","created_by":"cc-networkx","updated_at":"2026-04-24T11:02:03.000000000Z","closed_at":"2026-04-24T11:02:03.000000000Z","close_reason":"Pre-validate in Python wrapper; raise nx-exact messages per case","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
